Join the Pipe Foundation’s Impact in Sub-Saharan Africa with Bluepumps



This project is part of the educational program at the Computational Social Science bachelor program of the University of Amsterdam. The results of this study will be used for educational purposes. This project was developed with Join the Pipe; data and results will be shared with this organization. By the end of the project, students will create a website utilizing HTML, CSS, Python-Flask, and JavaScript.



Identifying How Behavioral Change Can Impact Users To Donate To Join the Pipe Foundation



You are invited to participate in this study by A/B testing to understand your perspective on ‘How Effective Is It To Gather Donations Through QRs on Bottles or Qualtrics for Join the Pipe Foundation, as Compared to Join the Pipe’s Website?’. Participants will be involved in responding to questions about Join the Pipe and about their experience and or thoughts about Join the Pipe Foundation’s website about Bluepumps in Sub-Saharan Africa.



Confidentiality



Your privacy as a participant is protected in this study, and your responses will be unidentifiable. Any reports generated will use only paraphrased wording or quotes that cannot be used to identify you. Further information can be found on Jointhepipe-foundaton.org under Privacy Policy.



Withdrawal



Participation in A/B testing is voluntary; it is entirely up to you to choose whether or not to participate. You can withdraw at any time or refuse to answer questions without consequences. If you experience discomfort, you may discontinue participating in this A/B testing.



Contact



The study is conducted by Maksymilian Czarnecki, Ameer Hussein, Cristian-Ioan Tomus, Quanpu Xiao, Raven Haesakkers, Sebastian Graff, and Atlas Sayin students at the University of Amsterdam.
